            <p>Philadelphia June 3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> 1885<lb/></p>
            <p>Reverend &#38; Venerable Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>In anticipation of an event fraught with joy <del>glad</del><lb/><del>ness</del> your colleagues&#44; expressly convened together&#44; beg to offer<lb/> their felicitations in unison of sentiments. They con&#45;<lb/>ceive that the assurance of their kind wishes will be gra&#45;<lb/>tifying to your feelings&#44; in the forthcoming celebration.<lb/> <del>The f</del> These few lines are designed to convey&#44; however feebly&#44;<lb/> a joint expression of sincere good will.<lb/></p>
            <p>To have reached the three score years and ten&#44; which the inspired<lb/> Psalmist deemed the term of life&#44; and to retain one&#39;s fa&#45;<lb/>culties unimpaired&#44; and without the power and will to pursue<lb/> a sacred calling&#44; is a heavenly blessing. That invaluable<lb/> boon you are permitted <del>fully</del> to enjoy. You have therefore<lb/> a real cause for gladness.<lb/></p>
            <p>While your Congregation will&#44; <del>by and &#91;&#63;&#93;</del> offer thanksgivings<lb/> in a fitting <del>Synagogual&#91;&#63;&#93;</del> service&#44; your coworkers in a religious<lb/> field&#44; pray that you may abide here in happiness.  They<lb/> entreat the Lord &#34;in whose hand is the soul of all living&#34;&#44; that<lb/> those you hold dear on earth may share your increased felicity&#44;<lb/> during a &#94; long protracted existence.<lb/></p>
            <p>E. Eppstein		Secretary<lb/>
                In behalf of the Board of Hebrew Ministers<lb/></p>
        </body>
